{{Quote|I can't honestly say I spent hours agonizing over it, because I didn't. It was five lines, and the costume did all the acting for me. It's on the page and you do it. But it was incredible fun and I had a great time doing it.|Ayesha Dharker, about the making of Episode II|<ref name="DSAQJ">{{SWArchive|url=episode-ii/bts/profile/f20020903/index.html|text=The Dharker Side: An Audience with Queen Jamillia}}</ref>}}
'''Ayesha Dharker''' (born [[March 16]], [[1977]]) is an [[Wikipedia:Indian people|Indian]] actress who played [[Queen]] [[Jamillia]] in [[Star Wars: Episode II Attack of the Clones|''Star Wars'': Episode II ''Attack of the Clones'']].

==Biography==
Dharker was born in [[Wikipedia:Mumbai|Bombay]], [[Wikipedia:India|India]]. Her father, [[Wikipedia:Anil Dharker|Anil Dharker]], is an Indian columnist and her mother, [[Wikipedia:Imtiaz Dharker|Imtiaz Dharker]], a British-Pakistani poet, artist and documentary filmmaker.

She made her screen debut in [[Wikipedia:François Villiers|François Villiers's]] film ''Manika: Une vie plus tard''. Dharker subsequently went on to star in many American, French and Indian films. She also appeared in several British TV series, such as [[Wikipedia:Doctors (TV series)|''Doctors'']], [[Wikipedia:Cutting It|''Cutting It'']], [[Wikipedia:Waking the Dead (TV series)|''Waking the Dead'']], [[Wikipedia:Coronation Street|''Coronation Street'']] and [[Wikipedia:The Indian Doctor|''The Indian Doctor'']]. She is best known to fans for appearing in [[Wikipedia:Doctor Who|''Doctor Who'']] in the episode "[[Wikipedia:Planet of the Ood|Planet of the Ood]]" as the character [[Tardis:Solana Mercurio|Solana Mercurio]].

Dharker also played the lead role of Malli in the film [[Wikipedia:The Terrorist (1997 film)|''The Terrorist'']], for which she won Best Artistic Contribution award at the [[1998]] [[Wikipedia:Cairo International Film Festival|Cairo International Film Festival]]. It was her role in this film that brought Dharker to the attention of [[Robin Gurland]], the casting director for ''Attack of the Clones''.<ref name="DSAQJ" />

Theatrically, Dharker played several stage roles, including [[Wikipedia:Scheherazade|Scheherazade]] in the [[Wikipedia:Royal Shakespeare Company|Royal Shakespeare Company's]] version of the ''Arabian Nights'' and [[Wikipedia:Mephistopheles|Mephastophilis]] in the [[Wikipedia:Bristol Old Vic|Bristol Old Vic's]] version of [[Wikipedia:Doctor Faustus (play)|''Doctor Faustus'']].

In [[2000]], Dharker appeared with [[Hugh Quarshie]] ([[Captain/Legends|Captain]] [[Quarsh Panaka/Legends|Quarsh Panaka]]) in the two-part TV miniseries [[Wikipedia:Arabian Nights (miniseries)|''Arabian Nights'']]. In [[2008]], she shared the screen with [[David Tennant]] (voice of [[Huyang/Legends|Huyang]] in [[Star Wars: The Clone Wars|''The Clone Wars'']]) in one episode of ''Doctor Who''.

